INTRODUCTION OF PROJECT¶

TARGET COLUMN == ATTRITION

  • Attrition--> Attrition is the departure of employees from the organization for any reason or in simple words we can say that employyees who left the company
  • ATTRITION "YEA"--> Employee left the organization
  • ATTRITION "NO"--> Employee not left the company

WHAT WE ARE GOING TO DO IN THIS

  • It will uncover the factors that lead to empoloyee attrtion
  • In this project we are going to analyse that how other features of dataset is effecting "attrition"

DOMAIN ANALYSIS¶

1.AGE age of an employee

2.BUSINESS TRAVEL That employee is traveling or not for business purpose.

3.DEPARTMENT In which department of company employee is working

4.DISTANCE FROM HOME That how much distance is there of an employee from hisher house to office.

5.HOURLY/DAILY/MONTHLY RATING Rating given to employee on daily, hourly and monthly basis.

6.EDUCATION FIELD From which education background employee belongs to

7.JOB AND ENVIRONMENT SATISFACTION It is that employee is satisfied with thier job as well as environment of office (given 1-5 ratings)

8.JOB INVOLVEMENT How much employee is involved in his work (Given in rating 1-5)

9.JOB LEVEL Level of job (Given in 1-5 rating). higher rating == higher job level

10.PERFORMANCE RATING How employee is performing according to his job (Given in 1-5 rating)

11.MONTHLY INCOME Monthly salary of an employee in dollars

12.PERCENTAGE SALARY HIKE How much percent salary in increasing annually

ANALYSIS ON CATEGORICAL COLUMNS With respect to Target Column (Attrition)

Target Column == Attrition

  • It can be seen that there is big difference in counts of the values so we can say that it is IMBALANCE DATA

In [30]:

plt.show()
  • Graph tells us that company has more count or more no of employees who travels rarely. it means travel rate of company is less
  • There are more employees which travels rarely and are not satisfied with thier job
  • Non-traveller have less count as well as less attrition
  1. IMPACT OF DEPARTMENT ON ATTRTTION
In [33]:
sns.countplot(x=df.Department, hue=df.Attrition)
plt.show()
  • There are 3 no.of department are there --> 1.Sales, 2.Reasearch and Development, 3.Human Resource
  • Research and Development department have more number of attrition(150 employees) as compared to other two department
  • HR Department have least attrition with just 5 to 10 employees
  1. IMPACT OF EDUCATION FIELD ON ATTTRTION
In [38]:
sns.countplot(x=df.Attrition, hue=df.EducationField)
plt.show()
  • First and foremost thing is that employees who are from Life Science and Medical Backgrounds are more as compared to other education fields
  • Nearly 100 number of employees are there who are from Life Science education backgroudn left the company and followed by Medical educatiobn employees
  • As we conclude from analysisi of Department and Attrition. here aalso HR Educational background employees have least Attrition.
  1. GENDER AND ATTRTION
In [39]:
sns.countplot(x=df.Attrition, hue=df.Gender)
plt.show()
  • Male employees are more as compared to Females
  • Males are more likely to quit the job rather than Females
  1. OVERTIME AND ATTRITION
In [40]:
sns.countplot(x=df.Attrition, hue=df.OverTime)
plt.show()
  • As for Attrition yes there is minor difference between the employees who are doing overtime and who are not doing overtime
  • So we can say that overtime feature is not muc effecting attrition
  • But we can conclude that most of employees are not doing overtime
  1. IMPACT OF JOB ROLE ON ATTRITION

  • Apart from these, it can also be seen that there are more number of employees in Sales Executive job role.

CATEGORICAL DATA HANDLING¶

In [74]:
df.Attrition=df.Attrition.map({"Yes":1, "No":0})
In [75]:
df.BusinessTravel=df.BusinessTravel.map({"Travel_Frequently":1,"Travel_Rarely":2,"Non-Travel":0})
In [76]:
df.Department=df.Department.map({"Research % Development":2, "Sales":1, "Human Resource":0})
In [84]:
df.EducationaField=df.EducationField.map({"Life Science":5, "Medical":4, "Marketing":3, "Technical Degree":2, "Other":1, "Human Resource":0})
In [12]:
df.JobRole=df.JobRole.map({"Laboratory Technician":8, "Sales Executive":7, "Research Scientist":6, "Sales Representative":5,
                           "Human Resources":4, "Manufacturing Director":3, "Health Representative":2, "Manager":1, "Research Director":0})
In [14]:
df.MaritalStatus=df.MaritalStatus.map({"Single":2,"Married":1, "Divorced":0})
In [16]:
df.OverTime=df.OverTime.map({"Yes":1, "No":0})
